description_en:
Already in 1704 S. Truchet had pointed out that, by paving the floor with a square tile in which two quarters of a circle of radius l/2 , having their center in two opposite vertices, are drawn, and arranging the tiles with random orientation, closed figures are obtained, whose shape goes from the simple circle to very tortuous closed paths. 
In this artwork, a Truchet pattern contained in a square has been reported in the complex plane with the transformation z → z2, from which the almond shape of the figure is derived. In doing so, the figure is folded back on itself, and a bulge is formed, to which the title of the work alludes.
A Gaussian distribution of white points on a black background along the path creates the central light.
    
